<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-267-050  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 267 050.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  March 12 1990 n581 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Interleaf breeds smart documents. (Interleaf Inc.'sactive-document object-oriented document management system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lieberman, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Interleaf Inc demonstrated a new 'active document' object-orientedtechnology at a recent Seybold Conference in Boston that allowsprograms, data and actions to be encapsulated into an object.andO;This allows smart, customized documents to be created that canfind and retrieve data from a corporate database, for example, andadd voice annotation before distributing themselveselectronically, among other functions.andP;  Several demos at theconference showed functions of active documents, includingreformatting a document automatically to a specific user'spreference and signalling when a corporate limit has beenexceeded.andP;  The live links provided by some vendors that allowdocuments to update their contents automatically are far surpassedby Interleaf's system, which creates documents that areintelligent enough to change themselves based on rules, standingor changing instructions, conditions met, events or the arrival ofnew data.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Interleaf Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    LEAF.andO;Topic:     Document Management SystemsNew TechniqueTechnologyInformation Storage and RetrievalObject-Oriented Data BasesInformation Resources ManagementElectronic PublishingEnhancements.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Interleaf's active document. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>